1 Introduction

The aim of this final project, is to apply advanced methods for time series forecast to stock market prices. Stock prices are one of the principal assets to invest nowadays, and trying to understand the behavior of the stock prices is key to make a wise investment. Although there are many technical insights which tries to detect upwards and downwards trends, those methods are not proven to work well for medium-term. We will apply many different algorithms and techniques to understand if this complex problem can be addressed with a structured way.

We will try to predict stock prices in a 1 month horizon. This is larger than the typical values adopted for technical analysis, but is a better horizon to make short term investment without falling into the day trading strategies.

# Initialize an empty list to store the closing prices
closing_prices <- list()

time_series_list <- list()

# Loop over each ticker in the list
for (ticker in tickers) {

  endpoint <- "https://eodhistoricaldata.com/api/eod/"

  # Set the parameters for the API request
  params <- list(api_token = api_key,
                 symbol = ticker, 
                 period = "d",
                 order = "d",
                 from = "2011-01-01", 
                 to = "2023-03-01") 
  
  # Construct the API query URL
  query_url <- paste0(endpoint, params$symbol, '.US?from=', params$from, '&to=', params$to, '&period=d&fmt=json&api_token=', api_key)
  
  # Send a GET request to the API endpoint and parse the response
  response <- GET(query_url)
  
  response_content <- content(response, "text", encoding = 'UTF-8')
  response_data <- fromJSON(response_content, flatten = TRUE)
  
  # Extract the closing price data from the response
  closing_prices <- response_data[, c("date", "adjusted_close")]

  time_series_list <- append(time_series_list, closing_prices)
  
}

After putting all together, we can print the first rows of the data. The data gathered is obtained since 2011 and has stock prices for every day in which the stock market has open (251 days per year aprox.).

Is it clear that no seasonality appears for any of the companies prices. Maybe, more volatility is seen at the end of the year for some companies like Apple (AAPL), Microsoft (MSFT), Procter & Gamble (PG).

3 Data transformation

We will transform the initial data set to make the data stationary:

\[y_j = (y_j-y_{j-1})/y_j\]

# Define a custom function to apply to each row
transformation <- function(x) {
  result <- (diff(x) / x)[-1]
  return(result)
}

# Apply the function to each row using apply()
result <- apply(ts, 2, transformation)

# Convert the result back to a time series object
ts_trans <- ts(result, frequency = 251, start = c(2011, 1))
colnames(ts_trans) <- colnames(ts)

autoplot(ts_trans) + ggtitle("Time series prices")

We can appreciate that the resulting time series are stationary. Some high variance is observed by the year 2020, but we will consider still valid for this analysis.

ggAcf(ts_trans, lag.max = 251) + ggtitle("Correlograms for stock prices prediction transformated")

After transforming the data set, the variables seems uncorrelated, almost all the values are inside the confidence interval.

4 Vector Auto Regressive Model

For extracting the relations between those time series, we can use a vector auto regressive model, in which every variable affects the other. This section was constructed following code on [2].

library(tsibble)
library(tidyverse) # great collection of packages to visualize and manage datasets  
library(lubridate) # to work with dates
library(fpp3)

To work with the vars package, we have to transform the time series object into a tsibble.

ts_tran_df <- as.data.frame(ts_trans)

One important thing to do, is to fill every NA value with the previous value. The stock market does not operate on weekends and holidays, so we can assume the price is constant for those periods.

# Generate a data frame with dates and stock prices:
df1 <- cbind(stock_prices$date[-1],ts_tran_df)
names(df1)[1] <- 'date'

# Pass it to tsibble:
ts_tsibble <- as_tsibble(df1)
## Using `date` as index variable.
# Make the NA values for the days missing:
ts_data_padded <- ts_tsibble %>% padr::pad()
## pad applied on the interval: day
# Fill those NAs with previous vlaues:
ts_tsibble3 <- ts_data_padded %>% tidyr::fill(AAPL,MSFT,GOOGL,PG,AMZN,TSLA,BRK,JNJ,JPM,V) %>% as_tsibble()
## Using `date` as index variable.

Later, we can model the vector autoregressive. For doing that, we can perform the training with all the values before 2023, and then use January, February of 2023 as testing. We will perform three models, one that is the classical AR(1), with all the terms for the one lag autoregressive, and then other which minimize BIC and AIC.

# Define the VAR model using the formula interface:
fit <-  ts_tsibble3 %>% filter(year(date)<2023) %>%
        fabletools::model(
             var_1 = fable::VAR(vars(AAPL,MSFT,GOOGL,PG,AMZN,TSLA,BRK,JNJ,JPM,V) ~ 0+AR(1)),
             aicc  = fable::VAR(vars(AAPL,MSFT,GOOGL,PG,AMZN,TSLA,BRK,JNJ,JPM,V), ic='aicc'),
             bic  = fable::VAR(vars(AAPL,MSFT,GOOGL,PG,AMZN,TSLA,BRK,JNJ,JPM,V), ic='bic')
             )
# Check the characteristics of those models:
glance(fit)

5 Vector Autoregressive for high dimension

For avoiding over fitting, shrinkage models as Lasso or Ridge penalization can be added to the model. We will use Lasso penalty for selecting a VAR model. However, over fitting does not seems to be happening, as flat forecast are made, we can run it still. This code is inspired from the code in [3].

The testing set will be of 1 year, and the training and tuning of the L1 hyper parameter will be done with cross-validation.

library(bigtime)

VAR.L1 <- bigtime::sparseVAR(Y=scale(as.matrix(head(ts_tsibble3[,-1],-30))), # leave 30 days for testing
                              h = 30, # evaluate forecasts 1 day ahead
                              selection = "cv", # using time series cross-validation
                              VARpen = "L1") # using the lasso penalty)

plot_cv(VAR.L1)

LhatL1 <- lagmatrix(fit=VAR.L1, returnplot=TRUE)

recursiveforecast(VAR.L1, h=10)$fcst

6 Machine Learning applied to time series

After performing the VAR methods, we can compute many of the machine learning techniques applied to time series. For doing this, we will: generate a train/test split, compute the methods, generate a âcross validationâ with mooving training window, compute the methods and obtain forecast with the confidence intervals for those models. The code applied in this section is inspired by the code from [3] and [4].

First, load some libraries:

library(tidyverse) # great collection of packages to visualize and manage datasets  
library(lubridate) # to work with dates
library(fpp3)
library(tsibble) # tidy data structure for time series
library(tidymodels) # machine learning ecosystem of packages (the new caret)
library(modeltime) # automatic forecasting using machine learning
library(modeltime.ensemble) # ensembles   
library(timetk) # similar to tidyverse but for time series (visualization and management of times series)
library(recipes)
library(utils)
library(randomForest)

6.1 Train-Test split

The objective of this project is to find a suitable model to forecast stock prices in a 30 days horizon. To do this, we can set many train and test sets, with a sliding window, to compute the model and then get the average performance for that model.

ts_tsibble3$date <- as.Date(ts_tsibble3$date) 

lag_roll_transformer_grouped <- function(data){
    data %>%
        group_by(Category) %>%
        tk_augment_differences(Change, .lags = 1, .differences=1) %>%
        ungroup()
                                              }
ts.tidy <- pivot_longer(ts_tsibble3,c(2:11),
                        names_to = "Category",
                        values_to = "Change")


# Lags include NAs that we need to remove
ts.tidy.feature <- ts.tidy %>%
                  lag_roll_transformer_grouped() %>%
                  drop_na()

The forecasting horizon will be the same as the previous section 30 days. Also, the window in which the model will be trained will be 180 days. Those periods are considered to be a good estimation, as stocks trends may change in a few months. Five slices of the cross validation for the Change variable can be see below:

splits_multi <- ts.tidy.feature %>% 
                time_series_cv(date_var = date, 
                                       initial     = "180 days", # window for train set
                                       assess      = "30 days", 
                                       skip        = "30 days", 
                                       slice_limit = 5, # maximum number of blocks/slices
                                       cumulative  = FALSE)
## Data is not ordered by the 'date_var'. Resamples will be arranged by `date`.
## Overlapping Timestamps Detected. Processing overlapping time series together using sliding windows.
# visualize the splits
splits_multi %>%
  tk_time_series_cv_plan() %>%
  plot_time_series_cv_plan(date,Change, .interactive = FALSE)

6.2 Recipe object

For training a Machine Learning model for time series forecasting in R, we should generate a recipe object which transforms the data set into a recipe object. This is a data frame-like object which has every instance and all the features involved. Two differenct recipes have been computed, in one of those, dates have been removed.

# Recipe without dates:

rec_obj <- recipe(Change ~ ., training(splits_multi$splits[[1]])) %>%
  step_timeseries_signature(date) %>%
  step_rm(date,date_index.num, date_half, date_quarter, date_month) %>%
  step_rm(contains("am.pm"), contains("hour"), contains("minute"),contains("day"),
  contains("second"), contains("xts"), contains("iso"), contains("month"),
  contains("year"), contains("week")) %>%  
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # remove variables with 0 variance
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())


# Recipe with dates (for NN and Adv.Prophet):

rec_obj_date <- recipe(Change ~ ., training(splits_multi$splits[[1]])) %>%
  step_timeseries_signature(date) %>%
  step_rm(date_index.num, date_half, date_quarter, date_month) %>%
  step_rm(contains("am.pm"), contains("hour"), contains("minute"),contains("day"),
  contains("second"), contains("xts"), contains("iso"), contains("month"),
  contains("year"), contains("week")) %>%  
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # remove variables with 0 variance
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())

6.3 Training Models for one slice

We can train many machine learning models for the last slice of the windows plotted in Section 6.1. In this case, the first slice will be the one that computes the metrics for the model, and the traning set can be seen in the corresponding plot.

We will train the following models:

  • Linear regression

  • Random forest

  • XG Boost

  • Neural network for time series forecast (NNETAR)

  • Prophet regression

For comparing with simpler methods, ARIMA, ETS and Prophet will be also calculated.

6.5 Training window optimization

After computing all the methods, the models are not performing as expected, so we can try many different training windows and see if the models improve.

We will set training windows of: 30, 180, 720 and 1440 days.

training_vec <- c(30,180,720,1440)

calib_list <- list()

for (i in 1:length(training_vec)){
  
  splits_multi <- ts.tidy.feature %>% 
                time_series_cv(date_var = date, 
                               initial     = paste0(training_vec[i],' days'), 
                               assess      = "30 days", 
                               skip        = "30 days", 
                               slice_limit = 5, 
                               cumulative  = FALSE, 
                               )
  
  ################################
  rec_obj <- recipe(Change ~ ., training(splits_multi$splits[[1]]),verbose(data_out = FALSE,data_in = FALSE,ssl=FALSE)) %>%
              step_timeseries_signature(date) %>%
              step_rm(date,date_index.num, date_half, date_quarter, date_month) %>%
              step_rm(contains("am.pm"), contains("hour"), contains("minute"),contains("day"),
              contains("second"), contains("xts"), contains("iso"), contains("month"),
              contains("year"), contains("week")) %>%  
              step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
              step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # remove variables with 0 variance
              step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors())

  ################################
  # Models
  sp <- 1

  model_spec_glmnet <- linear_reg(penalty = 0.01, mixture = 0.5) %>%
                        set_engine("glmnet")
  workflow_fit_glmnet <- workflow() %>%
                          add_model(model_spec_glmnet) %>%
                          add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
                          fit(training(splits_multi$splits[[sp]])
                          )
  
  model_spec_rf <- rand_forest(trees = 100, mode = "regression") %>%
                    set_engine("randomForest")
  workflow_fit_rf <- workflow() %>%
                    add_model(model_spec_rf) %>%
                    add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
                    fit(training(splits_multi$splits[[sp]])
                    )
  
  model_spec_xgboost <- boost_tree(mode = "regression") %>%
                        set_engine("xgboost")
  wflw_fit_xgboost <- workflow() %>%
                      add_model(model_spec_xgboost) %>%
                      add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
                      fit(training(splits_multi$splits[[sp]])
                      )
  
  ###########################
  model_table <- modeltime_table(
                workflow_fit_glmnet,
                workflow_fit_rf,
                wflw_fit_xgboost
                               ) 
  
  calibration_table <- model_table %>%
                      modeltime_calibrate(
                                          new_data = testing(splits_multi$splits[[sp]]),
                                          id = "Category"
                                          )
  
  ############################
  calib_list[i] <- calibration_table %>% 
                    modeltime_accuracy(acc_by_id = TRUE) %>% 
                    table_modeltime_accuracy(.interactive = FALSE)
  

}
for (i in 1:length(training_vec)){
 
  print(calib_list[i])

6.6 Recursive XGBoost

One last model that we can try for optimizing the forecasting, is the recursive XGBoost. First, we will train a model with the standard hyper parameters, and later we will tune them.

Generate the model for recursive XGBoost:

wflw_xgb <- workflow() %>%
            add_model(
                boost_tree(mode = "regression") %>% set_engine("xgboost")
            ) %>%
            add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
            fit(training(splits_multi$splits[[sp]])) 

# Set the recursive function:
wflw_xgb <- wflw_xgb %>%  
            recursive(
                id         = "Category", # We add an id = "id" to specify the groups
                transform  = lag_roll_transformer_grouped,
                train_tail = panel_tail(training(splits_multi$splits[[sp]]), Category, n=length(splits_multi$splits[[sp]])))

After calibrating the model, we can compute the metrics.

calib_tbl <- wflw_xgb %>% modeltime_table %>%

      id       = "Category"

  • Learning rate

  • Number of tries

parallel_start(6) # parallel computing with 3 cores

  learn_rate = c(0.3, 0.4, 0.5, 0.6),

) %>%
  create_model_grid(
    f_model_spec = boost_tree,
    engine_name  = "xgboost",

7 Conclusions

After performing several time series forecasting techniques, the following conclusions can be obtained:

  • The variability of the stock prices due to demand and supply constant changes, cannot be well estimated with the applied techniques. Some improvements could be to analyze the optimal horizon to consider, which in this project was considered fixed of 1 month.

  • The best performing algorithm is the NN for TS forecast, followed by others such as linear regression, XGboost and random forest.

  • The introduction of the recurrence for XGBoost has not contributed into getting better results.

  • The introduction of Lasso penalty for the VAR model has not contributed into a better metrics of the model, because the initial model was not over fitting the data.

  • Companies which are less volatile are easier to forecast, considering that these companies are the 10 biggest companies in the US stock market, it could be said that other companies would achive worst metrics if the same procedure was applied.
